{"status":"success","result":"Okay. Honest answer now that I've actually read it:\n\n*What's working correctly:*\n• Fire-and-forget grading is clean — zero user latency\n• Only storing non-correct grades is smart — avoids noise\n• `usedSecretary` flag correctly gates it so regex fallbacks don't get graded\n• Last 5 corrections injected into classify prompt — the `.slice(-5)` is there, changelog was accurate\n\n*Real problems:*\n\n*The coordinator grades itself with no context.* `gradeSecretaryResponse` gets the user message, the classification, and the coordinator's response — but no conversation history. For any follow-up question in a multi-turn conversation, the grader can't assess routing quality properly because it doesn't know what came before.\n\n*The grading is structurally biased upward.* The coordinator grades from its own perspective — \"was the routing right for ME?\" But the coordinator always handled it fine because it ran. It can't easily detect when it was *over-engineered* for the task. A simple question routed to analyst tier gets answered well... and the coordinator grades that as \"correct\" because it handled it, not because the tier was necessary. Suboptimal routing in the \"too powerful\" direction will almost never get flagged.\n\n*Coordinator response truncated at 400 chars for grading.* Long responses get graded on their opening only. A response that starts confidently but trails off into confusion would be graded as accurate.\n\n*The grading call uses qwen3.5:35b at 20s timeout.* For every conversational turn, this fires a full inference call in the background. On a busy day that's significant background load — the coordinator is doing double duty on every message.\n\n*What could be better:*\n• Pass the last 2-3 history messages to `gradeSecretaryResponse` for context\n• Add a \"was this tier necessary or overkill?\" dimension to the routing grade — not just correct/wrong, but efficient/correct/overkill\n• Use the Secretary itself for grading — cheaper, and it has skin in the game\n• Grade coordinator response truncation should be higher, or grade on the *outcome* (did it escalate? did it apologise?) rather than the text\n\nThe core design is right. The execution has real gaps worth fixing.","newSessionId":"9ab085a0-060d-41ae-b3d8-a97f4d571171"}
---NANOCLAW_OUTPUT_END---
---NANOCLAW_OUTPUT_START---
