{"status":"success","result":"No.\n\nThinking mode trades latency for reasoning quality. For most messages — routing decisions, short answers, status checks, casual conversation — the overhead isn't justified by the output improvement.\n\nThe current design is correct: default to fast, escalate to thinking when the task warrants it. The question is whether the *threshold* is calibrated right, which is exactly what the secretary feedback loop is supposed to tune over time.\n\nWhere always-on thinking would genuinely help: irreversible decisions, architectural recommendations, anything where a confident wrong answer has real cost. But that's a small fraction of total interactions.\n\nThe more useful question for this project: is the current threshold *too low* or *too high*? If Jarvis is triggering thinking mode on casual questions, that's waste. If he's answering hard questions in fast mode, that's quality loss. The feedback file will show which direction the calibration error is running — once there's enough data in it.","newSessionId":"9ab085a0-060d-41ae-b3d8-a97f4d571171"}
