{"status":"success","result":"This is a strong idea. Let me think through it fully.\n\nYou're describing two distinct but connected systems:\n\n*1. Performance SLA tracking*\n\nEvery response already has the data: model used, task type, complexity, think flag, elapsed time, whether escalation happened. That gets written to a structured log per response. Over time you build a baseline: \"code/high complexity/analyst tier averages 45s.\" When a response takes 180s for the same category, that's an anomaly worth investigating — model loaded cold, runaway tool loop, something else.\n\n*2. User dissatisfaction as a signal*\n\n\"Try harder\", \"no\", \"that's wrong\", \"escalate\" — these are explicit negative signals that are currently just... handled and forgotten. Capturing them as flags on the preceding response turns them into training data. You can then ask: was the bad response a routing failure, an inference failure, or a system error? Those have different fixes.\n\n*Where these two connect — the over-escalation detector:*\n\nThis is the most valuable part. Right now we can only detect under-escalation (model struggles, apologises, escalates). Over-escalation is invisible — the 35b analyst handles a \"what's 2+2\" perfectly and nobody knows it was wasteful.\n\nBut if you have SLA data showing analyst-tier latency on low-complexity tasks, AND those tasks never generate user dissatisfaction signals, that's the over-escalation signature. Fast tier would have handled it fine.\n\n*The \"call to supervisor\" pattern on dissatisfaction:*\n\nWhen a user signals failure — not just escalate-the-model, but flag-the-response — that's worth treating differently from a normal escalation. It should:\n- Retry at a higher tier with explicit context that the previous answer was rejected\n- Store the original response + rejection as a graded pair\n- Not just silently upgrade — acknowledge to the user that it's trying again with more depth\n\n*What needs more thought before bringing to Claude:*\n\nHow do you distinguish \"wrong answer\" from \"wrong topic\" — sometimes a user says \"no\" because Jarvis misunderstood the question, not because the model was insufficient. Those have different remedies. The signal capture needs to include enough context to tell them apart.\n\nWorth designing that distinction clearly before implementing.","newSessionId":"9ab085a0-060d-41ae-b3d8-a97f4d571171"}
---NANOCLAW_OUTPUT_END---
---NANOCLAW_OUTPUT_START---
{"status":"success","result":"Agreed. Flag it as a known limitation in the metadata design, not a blocker. Build the capture mechanism now, solve the disambiguation later when there's real data to look at.\n\nThe backlog item would be something like:\n\n*\"User dissatisfaction signal — distinguish misunderstanding vs. insufficient answer\"*\n- Blocked by: having real dissatisfaction data to analyze\n- Approach TBD: likely needs conversation context comparison between the rejected response and the retry\n- Dependencies: SLA tracking + signal capture need to ship first\n\nThat's a good pattern for us generally — capture the idea, note what's unresolved, don't let the unresolved part block the solvable part.\n\nWant me to maintain a running ideas backlog here that we can periodically sync with Claude's implementation backlog?","newSessionId":"9ab085a0-060d-41ae-b3d8-a97f4d571171"}
