{"status":"success","result":"That's a clean taxonomy. Let me pressure-test it:\n\n*Behavioral* — the model did what it was told but the behavior itself is wrong. Prompt/persona issue. Fix is in the system prompt or routing logic.\n\n*Data* — the model had bad or missing information. Stale knowledge, no web access, wrong context injected. Fix is in memory, web search, or context management.\n\n*Code* — something broke in the infrastructure. Tool call failed, IPC error, timeout, wrong model loaded. Fix is in the codebase.\n\n*Input* — the user's request was ambiguous or underspecified. The model did its best with what it had. Fix is clarification UX — Jarvis should have asked before proceeding.\n\n*Directive* — the routing or escalation decision was wrong. Right model, wrong tier, or wrong task type classification. Fix is in the Secretary or escalation logic.\n\nThe value of this taxonomy is that each category has a different owner and a different fix path. Behavioral and directive errors are Claude's domain. Data errors might be Jarvis's memory or web access. Code errors go straight to the bug tracker. Input errors point to UX improvements.\n\nOne gap: some failures will be multi-cause. A bad response could be *directive* (wrong tier) AND *data* (missing context). The classification should support compound labels, not force a single root cause.\n\nWorth adding that as a note on the backlog item.","newSessionId":"9ab085a0-060d-41ae-b3d8-a97f4d571171"}
---NANOCLAW_OUTPUT_END---
---NANOCLAW_OUTPUT_START---
{"status":"success","result":"That's a much more precise taxonomy. Let me restate it cleanly:\n\n*Behavioral* — unexpected/quirky output that doesn't match the designed behavior. Not necessarily breaking, but not what the system was supposed to do. Indicates a gap between intent and implementation — could be an edge case, an emergent interaction between components, or an undertested path.\n\n*Data* — unexpected state. Bad cache, corrupt config, interrupted process leaving stale state. The logic is correct, the data it's operating on isn't. Hard to fully prevent, but good startup validation and state integrity checks reduce frequency.\n\n*Input* — user or maintainer provided something the system didn't handle gracefully. Defensive coding, sanitization, and better error messaging are the levers. Every input error is also a signal that a guard is missing.\n\n*Directive* — the system did exactly what it was told, but the instruction was wrong. Product owner oversight or developer error. System prompt, routing logic, escalation thresholds, feature decisions. This is where our backlog and Andy/Claude/DJ review loop is supposed to catch things before they ship.\n\n*Code* — I'd add this back as a fifth category. Pure implementation bugs — logic errors, off-by-ones, race conditions, unhandled exceptions. Distinct from directive (wrong instruction) and behavioral (unexpected but not crashing). This is what tests are supposed to catch.\n\nDoes code belong as its own category, or does it fold into one of the four?","newSessionId":"9ab085a0-060d-41ae-b3d8-a97f4d571171"}
---NANOCLAW_OUTPUT_END---
