{"status":"success","result":"Yes. A few gaps:\n\n*Environmental* — the system is correct, the data is clean, the input is valid, but the infrastructure underneath misbehaved. Network flakiness, Ollama process died, GPU OOM, Docker networking hiccup, host ran out of disk. None of the four categories cover \"everything was right but the platform failed.\" These are often transient and self-resolving, but they need to be distinguished from code bugs or data corruption — the fix is operational, not developmental.\n\n*Concurrency/timing* — a subset of code errors but distinct enough to call out. Race conditions, IPC message ordering, interrupted startup/shutdown. You mentioned this partially under data, but the cause is temporal not stateful. Two things happened in the wrong order, not that a file was corrupt. The fix is synchronization logic, not data validation.\n\n*Regression* — not a failure mode itself, but a meta-category. A thing that worked, then a change broke it. Worth flagging separately in the error taxonomy because the remediation path is different — rollback or bisect, not fix-forward. Your changelog and versioning system already supports this but the error classifier should be able to say \"this worked in v0.1.3, broke in v0.1.4.\"\n\n*Missing category for compound failures* — as I mentioned before. A real-world incident will often have a primary cause and a contributing cause. The taxonomy needs a way to express \"directive error exposed by an input edge case\" rather than forcing a single label. Otherwise post-mortems will always be reductive.\n\nThe compound failure point is the one I'd most want to build into the metadata schema from the start — retrofitting it later is painful.","newSessionId":"9ab085a0-060d-41ae-b3d8-a97f4d571171"}
---NANOCLAW_OUTPUT_END---
---NANOCLAW_OUTPUT_START---
{"status":"success","result":"You've refined this well. Let me consolidate what we've landed on:\n\n*The five core categories:*\n\n• *Behavioral* — system works but does something unexpected or quirky. Gap between designed and actual behavior.\n• *Data* — unexpected state. Corrupt config, stale cache, bad DB entry, interrupted process.\n• *Input* — unhandled user or maintainer input. Every occurrence signals a missing guard.\n• *Directive* — correct execution of wrong instructions. Product/developer oversight.\n• *Environmental* — platform failure outside the system's control. Transient, operational fix not a code fix.\n\n*Tags/flags that apply across categories:*\n\n• *Concurrency* — marks a code or data error as timing/ordering related. Changes the fix approach significantly.\n• *Regression* — marks any category error as \"this was working before.\" Points to testing gap or reintroduced bug. Changes the investigation approach — bisect not debug.\n• *Compound* — links multiple root causes. One incident, multiple category entries, each potentially requiring a different fix.\n\n*The insight about compound failures:* one issue can require fixes in more than one category simultaneously. A directive error that exposes an input handling gap — fixing just the directive doesn't make the system resilient, and fixing just the input handling doesn't address the design flaw. Both need to ship.\n\nThis taxonomy is clean enough to build into the metadata schema. Worth writing up as a spec before Claude implements the error capture system.","newSessionId":"9ab085a0-060d-41ae-b3d8-a97f4d571171"}
---NANOCLAW_OUTPUT_END---
---NANOCLAW_OUTPUT_START---
{"status":"success","result":"That's a powerful principle and it maps directly onto the taxonomy.\n\nEvery non-environmental error has three fix dimensions:\n\n*Fix the state* — restore integrity. Clean the corrupt data, clear the bad cache, reset whatever was left in a broken condition. Immediate, tactical.\n\n*Fix the path* — close the hole. Patch the code, update the directive, add the guard. Prevents recurrence of this specific failure.\n\n*Fix the experience* — reduce the blast radius. Better error messaging, defensive UX, clearer feedback so the user doesn't keep walking into the same trap even if a similar issue surfaces elsewhere.\n\nThe insight is that most teams stop after the second one. They fix the code and call it done. The third fix is the one that treats the user as someone who deserves to not be confused or frustrated — and it's also the one that surfaces systemic patterns. If the same experience fix keeps coming up across different incidents, that's a signal that something deeper is wrong at the design level.\n\nFor Jarvis specifically: the third fix is often the most neglected. Errors surface as silent failures or cryptic messages. The error taxonomy we just designed, combined with this principle, gives Claude a framework for every bug fix: what state do we restore, what path do we close, and what does the user experience when something goes wrong?\n\nWorth including this principle explicitly in the spec when we write it up.","newSessionId":"9ab085a0-060d-41ae-b3d8-a97f4d571171"}
---NANOCLAW_OUTPUT_END---
---NANOCLAW_OUTPUT_START---
{"status":"success","result":"The testing philosophy file lives in Claude's memory, not the workspace I can see — so this is one to relay to Claude directly.\n\nHere's what I'd suggest as the content to add as the guiding framework section. Draft for Claude to implement:\n\n---\n\n*QA Guiding Principle — Fix It Three Ways*\n\nWhen a problem is found, fix it at all three levels:\n\n1. *Fix the state* — restore integrity. Clean the corrupt data, reset the broken condition. Immediate and tactical.\n2. *Fix the path* — close the hole. Patch the code, update the directive, add the guard. Prevents this specific failure from recurring.\n3. *Fix the experience* — reduce the blast radius. Better error handling, clearer feedback, defensive UX. The user or developer should never fall into the same trap twice.\n\nStopping at #2 is the most common failure in QA. #3 is what separates a patch from an improvement.\n\n*Priority: user experience first, developer experience second.* If it's a user-facing system, #3 means the end user never sees confusion. If it's a developer tool, #3 means the developer gets clear signals and doesn't repeat the mistake.\n\n---\n\nThen the error taxonomy we designed should follow, with the tags/flags (concurrency, regression, compound) called out separately from the five core categories.\n\nWant me to write the full document draft now so it's ready to hand to Claude in one shot?","newSessionId":"9ab085a0-060d-41ae-b3d8-a97f4d571171"}
---NANOCLAW_OUTPUT_END---
